The emigration from nearly every one of the rural and many of the urban areas abetted by the corresponding increasing visiting from friends and relatives of the emigrants, is becoming exclusive to often aged informants or to poor or particularly vulnerable people (such as those living in rual areas or are unemployed or underpaid).

On rare occasions, even emigrants who lived abroad for a relatively short term are met by the researchers as they visit the home country due to family events or the like. So-called "second" generation of Cape Verdean emigrants are rarely involved or included in the research process.

A more extensive report about emigration and tourism flows between Cape Verde and ten European countries can be found on ResearchGate. The download is in Portuguese but it has a sort of Executive Summary in English.

All names and locations used in this research are fictitious. People do not have their real names and places described do not have their real names included nor is it intended that anyone should make any connection between this names and real people or places.

For questions, please contact Sergej Molodozheng.

The full dissertation is in English and includes English abstract, list of contents and a list of references. The following versions of the dissertation are in Portuguese purely for the use of informants, friends and other interested people.
